| After 9 Years, Bugzilla Moves Up to 3.0                            |
|   from the moving-on-up dept.                                      |
|   posted by Zonk on Saturday May 12, @03:27 (Bug)                  |
|   http://it.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/12/0641225           |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

BuggyUser writes "Bugzilla, the popular application to track and manage
software development bug reports, has [0]moved up to version 3.0. The 2.x
series has been in service for the last nine years. From the article:
'According to the Bugzilla 3.0 release announcement, some of the new
features in this version include custom fields, support for the Apache
mod_perl module, per-product permissions, an XML-RPC interface, and the
ability to create and edit bugs via email. A demo site has been set up
where users can test the new version before downloading.'" Linux.com and
Slashdot.org are both owned by OSTG.

Discuss this story at:
    http://it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/12/0641225

Links:
    0. http://applications.linux.com/applications/07/05/12/0234203.shtml?tid=49


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| NASA Gears Up for the Regolith Rumble                              |
|   from the in-this-corner-weighing-in-at-0.34-pounds dept.         |
|   posted by Zonk on Saturday May 12, @05:39 (NASA)                 |
|   http://science.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/12/0654212      |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]eldavojohn writes "NASA is holding [1]another scientific challenge to
see which autonomous robot can [2]move the most regolith in 30 minutes.
The finer details: 'To win the cash prizes for NASA's Regolith Challenge,
teams must demonstrate fully autonomous robots capable of collecting at
least 330 pounds (150 kilograms) of mock Moon dirt within 30 minutes.
Whichever robot moves the most regolith over the benchmark limit, while
still meeting contest specifications, wins, NASA said. But in order to
compete, lunar regolith excavators must weigh less than 88 pounds (40
kilograms) and run on less than 30 kilowatts of power, according to
contest rules.'"

Discuss this story at:
    http://science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/12/0654212

Links:
    0. mailto:djohnsop@gmu.edu
    1. http://www.californiaspaceauthority.org/regolith/
    2. http://www.space.com/businesstechnology/070511_regolith_challenge.html


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Posting Porn Link Judged Unlawful in Hong Kong                     |
|   from the touchy-on-titilation dept.                              |
|   posted by Zonk on Saturday May 12, @06:29 (Censorship)           |
|   http://yro.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/12/0659227          |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]hkxforce writes "Can you imagine posting a link to a website that
would get you arrested by the police? In Hong Kong, a middle-age man has
been [1]heavily fined for posting a porn link in an adult discussion
forum. 'A court in the Kwun Tong district of the city heard that Woo
provided a hyperlinked message on the forum which, when clicked, would
enable other forum users to access an overseas pornographic website
showing the photos. But Internet Society chairman Charles Mok Nai-kwong
said the court case raised several concerns. 'In this case, the court has
given a new direction to the public concerning the responsibility of
internet users,' he said. Mok added that he also believed the case could
damage the freedom of information on the internet. 'This man posted a
link on the internet which now becomes an act that constitutes the
breaking of law, and my question is whether a link is being regarded as
the 'obscene article,'' he said.'"

Discuss this story at:
    http://yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/12/0659227

Links:
    0. http://hkxforce.net/
    1. http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticleNew.asp?xfile=data/theworld/2007/May/theworld_May328.xml&section=theworld&col=


